      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Town Divided</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from NAACP official Oscar P Cohen comments on August 4 article in racial gap in schools in Nyack, NY (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Racial Gap in Schools Splits a Town Proud of Diversity'' (front page, Aug. 4), a parent says that no issue has divided the community more than the charge by the Nyack chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and Nyack Partners in Education that there are in effect two public school systems in Nyack, one for white students and one for students of color.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Racial Gap in Schools Splits a Town Proud of Diversity'' (front page, Aug. 4), a parent says that no issue has divided the community more than the charge by the Nyack chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and Nyack Partners in Education that there are in effect two public school systems in Nyack, one for white students and one for students of color.</p>
        <p>Given these parallel systems operating under one administration, the community has always been divided -- it's just that no one has dared  to talk about it. Now, people are talking. Truth doesn't necessarily divide; it's also the base for building a just society.</p>
        <p>OSCAR P. COHEN  Nyack, N.Y., Aug. 7, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is education committee chairman, N.A.A.C.P. Nyack chapter.</p>
      </block>
